From 5fe2044249940d1a71492e494a2fb34b8e1c27ce Mon Sep 17 00:00:00 2001
From: Igor Kanyuka <ifelmail@gmail.com>
Date: Mon, 24 Feb 2025 15:59:10 +0000
Subject: [PATCH 206/206] Map DBus event to RF MessageID and parse args

There is a generated map that contains DBus event name and corresponding
RF info - Registry, MessageID within the registry and names of arguments
to be translated from DBus and passed to the RF MessageArgs.
Use the map to map DBus events to translate DBus to corresponding
Redfish event to send it according to subscriptions and in LogServices
to populate MessageId and MessageArgs in LogEntry structure.

Current behavior of building LogEntries from DBus events is to use DBus
message as Redfish message and not populate MessageId and MessageArgs.
To preserve this behavior, the
BMCWEB_REDFISH_ALLOW_LOG_ENTRY_FROM_DBUS_WO_MAPPING option added to
meson and enabled by default. So the code will first try to map DBus
event to redfish event, if it can do that, MessageId, Resolution and
Severity from the registry will be used, and it will also use a message
from the registry replacing placeholders with values from the
MessageArgs. If it cannot be mapped, the message will either be dropped
if the option is disabled (needs to be disabled explicitly) or build the
message in the way it did before this change.

Binary size change (note, it's for the branch that includes several
upstream registries, and not only this change):
4152836->4263932 bytes. Delta is 111096 bytes, or 2.67% increase.

Testing:
- Unit tests
- Built an image with my code, ran it in QEMU:
1. Setup a subscription pointing to my receiver service.
2. Injected an entry with the command: [1]. It injected a DBus log entry
   with a name that has a corresponding RF message ID in the map. Note
the output contains ID of the event - 17.
3. BMCWeb sent event to the receiver. See [2] it's a debug from the
   receiver web service it logged raw payload.
4. Ran command to see pull the entry from the LogService using the event
   ID: [3]
5. Ran the same command for ID, which does not have mapping.
   See the output [4], you can see that the fields are populated for
the message that has mapping (#17) and missing for one that does not
have mapping (#14).
6. Ran rf_service_validator against running in QEMU instance.

[1] Command to inject a log entry and its output:
```
log-create xyz.openbmc_project.Sensor.Threshold.ReadingBelowLowerCriticalThreshold --json '{ "SENSOR_NAME": "BIC_JI_SENSOR_MB_RETIMER_TEMP_C", "READING_VALUE": 10.2, "UNITS": "xyz.openbmc_project.Sensor.Value.Unit.DegreesC", "THRESHOLD_VALUE": 15.5 }'

/xyz/openbmc_project/logging/entry/1
```

